    description: `## Premium walkthrough

### What this exact problem is asking
Making A Large Island asks for the largest island size possible after changing at most one 0 cell into 1. Islands are groups of 1s connected in four directions.

### Core intuition
First label every existing island with a unique id and record its size. Then inspect each 0 cell. If we flip that 0 to 1, it can connect the distinct island ids around it. The candidate size is 1 plus the sum of those neighboring island sizes. Use a set of neighboring ids so the same island is not counted twice.

### State meaning
idGrid stores which island each land cell belongs to. sizeById stores the area of every island id. The best answer tracks the largest existing island or best flip result.

### Invariant
After labeling, every 1 cell belongs to exactly one island id, and sizeById[id] is the exact cell count for that island.

### Mistakes to avoid
Do not count the same island twice when a 0 touches it from two sides. Do not forget the all-ones case, where no flip is needed and the answer is N * N. Do not include diagonal neighbors.

### Complexity
Labeling plus checking every cell is O(N squared). The id grid and size map use O(N squared) space.` ,
